BOX COX\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b\fs22 \cf2 OBJECTIVE
\b0\fs20 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 For indicators that still have skew and kurtosis values beyond the thresholds (after Winsorisation), this tab displays three transformations which can correct the skew/kurtosis. These transformations can be optionally used in the 
\b TreatedData tab
\b0 .\
 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b\fs22 \cf2 STEP-BY-STEP\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0\fs20 \cf0 1) Compare the skewness and kurtosis values for each alternative transformation\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b\fs22 \cf2 NOTES
\b0\fs20 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Indicators which exceed the skew/kurtosis thresholds are displayed here. There are four columns for each indicator.\
\
The first column is the untransformed data (also with no Winsorisation). The following three columns are as follows:\
\
* LN: ln transformation such that new min = 0\
new value = ln (old value  - old min + 1)\
\
* SQRT: square root transformation such that new min = 0\
new value = (old value - old min) ^ 0.5\
\
* LNMED: ln transformation and normalization such that min = 0, max = 1, median = 0.5:\
new value = 0.5 [ln [1 + (old value \'96 min) (max + min \'96 2 sample median) / ((sample median \'96 min) ^ 2)] / ln [(max \'96 sample median) / (sample median \'96 min)] * direction + 0.5 (1 - direction)\
\
The LNMED transformation forces the median to be equal to the mid-range value, which implies that in most cases skewness and kurtosis will be within the defined thresholds. \
\
Row 7 indicates which indicators still present problems for each transformation. If this is still the case after all transformations, an alternative transformation should be found outside of this tool.\
